title: For Sale:  French mas 1936 mle
postcontent:
MAS 1936 MLE standard issue for the foreign legion. Execellent condition. Collectors item shooter whatever you want. Stock is in beautiful shape and I kept the wood oiled and moist not refinished. Comes with grenade launcher and bayonet. Possibly arsenalrefurbished or never issued.
MAS 1936/ Mle 1936/ FRENCH M36. FRENCH MILITARY BOLT ACTION RIFLE, Caliber 7.5 mm French (M1929 cartridge), approx. 2700 feet per second muzzle velocity, effective range 400 meters with the issue iron sights. 5 round internal magazine loaded from the top individually or with charger clips. Overall length 40.1”, barrel length 22.6”, unloaded weight 8.29 lb. Produced by French government-owned Manufacture d'Armes de Saint-Étienne (MAS).
HISTORY: The MAS 1936 was successor to the French Lebel and Mannlicher-Berthier rifles of WWI through the 1930’s. Because of the peculiar rim and body shape of the Lebel cartridge, which made feeding difficult in automatic weapons, a modern rimless cartridge, the M1924, was developed, then modified resulting in the M1929 cartridge. The most successful of bolt action designs for the new rimless cartridge was the M1932, slightly modified and adopted as the MAS 1936. Production began in 1937, with interruptions during the German occupation of France, resuming post-war and continuing until 1952. Prior to the outbreak of WWII, the MAS 1936 was only produced in sufficient numbers for a few front-line French units. After the fall of France to Germany, the Wehrmacht adopted captured MAS 1936’s as the Gewehr 242(f) and issued them to some German occupying garrisons. Following WWII, France resumed production and the MAS 1936 was extensively used by French troops and colonial defense forces in Algeria, Indochina (VietNam), in the Mideast during the Suez Crisis, and elsewhere.
GENERAL DESCRIPTION: The MAS 1936 is compact, about 4” shorter than the U.S. Garand and German K98Kar rifles also used in WWII. Prominent features include a forward bent “dogleg” bolt handle, a 2-piece stock, stacking hook alongside the barrel, hooded front sight, and a wicked 17” cruciform spike bayonet stored under the barrel. The action is a modified Mauser type, with the main difference being the bolt locking lugs, which on the MAS 1936 are near the rear of the bolt and lock into recesses in the receiver bridge, rather than front bolt lugs engaging recesses directly behind the chamber.
